AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; The trial of French actor Gerard Depardieu will open on Monday before the Paris Criminal Court, on the charge of sexual abuse of two women during the filming of a film in 2021. The Oltralpe media report it. The former movie star who fell into disgrace, was accused of harassment, sexual abuse and rape by about twenty women, but this is the first case to end in court.
<br The trial process that will start on Monday concerns the accusations of sexual violence during the shooting of "Les Volets Verts" ("The Green Persians") > of director Jean Becker in 2021. Anouk Grinberg, a prominent actress appeared in the film, supported the two plaintiffs: a 54-year-old scenographer and a 34-year-old director. Both women report that they were victims of sexual violence.> Grinberg stated that Depardieu had consistently made "salky settlements", denouncing the fact that "when filmmakers hire Depardieu for a film, they know that they are hiring an abuser >".
Depardieu's health problems
<br The process, initially planned for last October, was <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-10-28/processo-gerard-depardieu-per-aggression-sexual-28463674/"> was postponed</a> due to the bad health conditions > of actor 76-year-old, who in his long career of success filmed more than 200 television films and series. Depardieu's lawyer, Jeremie Assous, reported in recent months that the actor had undergone a quadruple cardiac bypass and suffered from diabetes, aggravated by the stress of the imminent process. >
<br> Since then Depardieu has been visited by a medical expert appointed by the court, who has established that it is eligible to appear in court, but with reservations. According to his lawyer, Depardieu's courtrooms will be limited to six hours a day and will take breaks every time he "needs." Assous said that the actor "negades all charges in their totality".&nbsp;
One of the two accusers of Depardieu, the scenographer, reported in February of last year to have suffered obscene comments, sexual assaults, sexual harassment and sexist insults during the shooting. His testimony was raised by the French investigative website Mediapart>. "My client hopes this time the process goes on," said the scenographer's lawyer, Carine Durrieu-Diebolt.
The second plaintiff also denounced sexual violence. "What my client wants is that the trial takes place, but I'm also worried about how Depardieu's defense will treat civilians at the hearing," said lawyer Claude Vincent.
On the twenty-five complaints of the sacred monster of French cinema, several cases were filed by prescription. The French actress Charlotte Arnould was the first woman to press charges against Depardieu in 2018. Last August, the Paris Prosecutor requested a trial for rape and sexual violence, accusations that the actor has constantly denied over the years.
<br> "Never, but never, I abused a woman", wrote Depardieu i>n an open letter to the conservative newspaper Le Figaro. The actor is not alien to scandals, being finished in the newspapers for risses, driving in a state of drunkenness and urination in the corridor of an airplane. A 2023 French television documentary entitled "The Fall of the Ork", which highlights all the vulgarity > and the sexism of Depardieu during his trip to North Korea in 2018, even towards a child >, made a lot of stir in France.&nbsp;
